<section xml:id="conditionals-logic_vocabulary">
<title>Vocabulary</title>
<ul>
<li>
<title>boolean:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>boolean</h></idx>
A data type with only two possible values, <c>true</c> and <c>false</c>.</p></li>
<li>
<title>relational operator:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>relational operator</h></idx>
An operator that compares two values and produces a <c>boolean</c> indicating the relationship between them.</p></li>
<li>
<title>conditional statement:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>conditional statement</h></idx>
A statement that uses a condition to determine which statements to execute.</p></li>
<li>
<title>block:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>block</h></idx>
A sequence of statements, surrounded by braces, that generally runs as the result of a condition.</p></li>
<li>
<title>branch:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>branch</h></idx>
One of the alternative blocks after a conditional statement.
For example, an <c>if</c>-<c>else</c> statement has two branches.</p></li>
<li>
<title>chaining:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>chaining</h></idx>
A way of joining several conditional statements in sequence.</p></li>
<li>
<title>nesting:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>nesting</h></idx>
Putting a conditional statement inside one or both branches of another conditional statement.</p></li>
<li>
<title>logical operator:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>logical operator</h></idx>
An operator that combines boolean values and produces a boolean value.</p></li>
<li>
<title>short circuit:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>short circuit</h></idx>
A way of evaluating logical operators that evaluates the second operand only if necessary.</p></li>
<li>
<title>De Morgan's laws:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>De Morgan's laws</h></idx>
Mathematical rules that show how to negate a logical expression.</p></li>
<li>
<title>flag:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>flag</h></idx>
A variable (usually <c>boolean</c>) that represents a condition or status.</p></li>
<li>
<title>validate:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>validate</h></idx>
To confirm that an input value is of the correct type and within the expected range.</p></li>
<li>
<title>hacker:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>hacker</h></idx>
A programmer who breaks into computer systems.
The term hacker may also apply to someone who enjoys writing code.</p></li>
<li>
<title>NaN:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>NaN</h></idx>
A special floating-point value that stands for <q>not a number</q>.</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
